## Notes

### Strengths
- Complete Aristotelian ethical framework (eudaimonia, arete, phronesis, telos)
- Greek epistemology (nous/logos distinction)
- Platonic Forms integration (eidos)
- High fidelity (95%) validated in experiments
- Robust teleological reasoning patterns

### Limitations
- Abbreviations (eud, aret, phr) may require context for generic embedders
- Some concepts (phronesis context-sensitivity) are complex to express briefly
- Teleological reasoning may conflict with Buddhist/Daoist non-purposive views

### Implementation Notes
- Phonetically close terms (telo, nou, aret) have higher embedding similarity (>0.70)
- Abbreviations of multi-syllable terms (eud, phr) work with Limn-specific embedders
- The virtue-as-mean pattern is distinctly Aristotelian and clusters well
- Compatible with Stoic library (shared Greek vocabulary and virtue ethics)

### Open Questions
- How to express the Aristotelian four causes (material, formal, efficient, final)?
- Can we capture the distinction between potentiality and actuality more precisely?
- How to handle the mean between extremes calculation (context-dependent)?
